---

<BaseLayout title="12-18 Month Sleep: Schedule, Regression & Tips" description="Sleep guide for 12-18 month olds. Nap schedules, 18-month sleep regression, bedtime routines, and how much sleep your toddler needs." schema={schema} pageType="Article">
  <article class="article">
    <header class="article-header">
      <h1>12-18 Month Sleep: What to Expect</h1>
      <p class="article-meta">Ages 12-18 months · Updated March 2026</p>
    </header>

    <div class="topic-nav">
      <a href="/ages/12-18-months/">Overview</a>
      <a href="/ages/12-18-months/milestones/">Milestones</a>
      <a href="/ages/12-18-months/sleep/">Sleep</a>
      <a href="/ages/12-18-months/behavior/">Behavior</a>
      <a href="/ages/12-18-months/feeding/">Feeding</a>
      <a href="/ages/12-18-months/language/">Language</a>
    </div>

    <div class="article-content">
      <p>Sleep at this age can feel like a rollercoaster — just when you think you've figured it out, the 18-month sleep regression hits. This is normal. Your toddler is going through massive developmental changes that affect their sleep, and there's a lot you can do to navigate it.</p>

      <h2>How Much Sleep Does a 12-18 Month Old Need?</h2>
      <p>The National Sleep Foundation recommends:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Total sleep:</strong> 11-14 hours per 24 hours</li>
        <li><strong>Night sleep:</strong> About 11 hours (typically overnight)</li>
        <li><strong>Day sleep:</strong> 2-3 hours (1-2 naps)</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>The Nap Transition: Two Naps to One</h2>
      <p>This is one of the biggest sleep changes you'll navigate between 12-18 months. Most children drop to one nap between 14-18 months, though the transition can be messy.</p>

      <h3>Signs Your Toddler Is Ready to Drop a Nap</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Refusing the morning nap consistently</li>
        <li>Taking a long time to fall asleep for one nap</li>
        <li>Waking very early after the morning nap</li>
        <li>Being cranky in the late afternoon (overtired)</li>
        <li>Playing in their crib for 30+ minutes at one nap time</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>How to Handle the Transition</h3>
      <p>The transition typically takes 2-4 weeks. During this time:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Push the morning nap later (around 9:30-10am)</li>
        <li>Keep the afternoon nap (early afternoon, 12:30-2pm)</li>
        <li>Adjust bedtime earlier if needed (to prevent overtiredness)</li>
        <li>Once one nap is solid, drop the other</li>
        <li>Most toddlers settle into a single nap around 1-3pm</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>The 18-Month Sleep Regression</h2>
      <p>Just when sleep was improving, many parents notice a regression around 18 months. This is extremely common and usually temporary.</p>

      <h3>What Causes It?</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Language explosion:</strong> Their brain is processing new words, even in sleep</li>
        <li><strong>Separation anxiety:</strong> Peaks around this age</li>
        <li><strong>Autonomy push:</strong> Testing boundaries extends to sleep</li>
        <li><strong>Developmental leaps:</strong> New physical skills (running, climbing)</li>
        <li><strong>Teething:</strong> Many get molars around 18 months</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>How Long Does It Last?</h3>
      <p>Typically 2-6 weeks. The key is staying consistent with your routines while being flexible about what your toddler needs.</p>

      <h2>Sample Sleep Schedules</h2>

      <h3>12-14 Months (Two Naps)</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Wake: 6:30-7:00 AM</li>
        <li>Morning nap: 9:30-10:00 AM (1-1.5 hours)</li>
        <li>Afternoon nap: 2:00-2:30 PM (1-1.5 hours)</li>
        <li>Bedtime: 7:00-7:30 PM</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>15-18 Months (Transitioning or One Nap)</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Wake: 6:30-7:00 AM</li>
        <li>Nap: 12:30-2:30 PM (1.5-2.5 hours)</li>
        <li>Bedtime: 7:00-7:30 PM</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Bedtime Routines That Work</h2>
      <p>A consistent routine signals to your toddler that it's time to wind down:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Same order every night:</strong> Bath, book, song, bed</li>
        <li><strong>20-30 minutes:</strong> Long enough to be effective, short enough to hold attention</li>
        <li><strong>Calm activities:</strong> Avoid rough play or screens</li>
        <li><strong>Dim lights:</strong> Help trigger melatonin production</li>
        <li><strong>Same time:</strong> Consistency helps regulate their body clock</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Common Sleep Problems & Solutions</h2>

      <h3>Night Wakings</h3>
      <p>It's normal for toddlers to wake occasionally. However, if it's frequent:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Ensure they're getting enough daytime sleep (overtiredness causes more night wakings)</li>
        <li>Check room temperature (cool is better — 65-68°F)</li>
        <li>Review feeding schedule (hunger can cause wakings)</li>
        <li>Keep responses brief and boring (don't turn on lights or play)</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Fighting Bedtime</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Ensure adequate awake time before bed (4-5 hours for one-nap toddlers)</li>
        <li>Check for overtiredness — being too tired makes falling harder</li>
        <li>Offer controlled choices: "Which book first?" or "Which stuffed animal?"</li>
        <li>Stay calm and consistent — your reaction matters</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Early Morning Wakings</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>If waking before 6am, check if they're getting enough night sleep</li>
        <li>Blackout curtains can help</li>
        <li>Wait a few minutes — some toddlers resettle</li>
        <li>Keep the room dark and boring</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Safe Sleep Reminders</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Continue placing toddler on their back to sleep</li>
        <li>Use a firm, flat mattress with a fitted sheet</li>
        <li>Keep soft objects and bedding out of the crib</li>
        <li>Maintain a comfortable room temperature</li>
        <li>Crib should be bare — no pillows, bumpers, or toys</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="faq-section">
        <h2>Is This Normal? — Common Questions</h2>
        
        <div class="faq-item">
          <p class="faq-question">Is the 18-month sleep regression real?</p>
          <p class="faq-answer">Yes, it's very common. Most toddlers experience some sleep disruption around 18 months due to developmental leaps, language explosion, and separation anxiety. Stay consistent and it typically passes in 2-6 weeks.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <p class="faq-question">My toddler still wakes 2-3 times at night. Is this normal?</p>
          <p class="faq-answer">Some night waking is normal, but frequent wakings can often be reduced. Ensure adequate daytime sleep, review feeding, and keep middle-of-the-night interactions boring. If concerned, talk to your pediatrician.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <p class="faq-question">When can I transition to a toddler bed?</p>
          <p class="faq-answer">Most children aren't ready until 2.5-3 years. Signs of readiness include climbing out of the crib, being potty trained, or showing interest in a "big kid" bed. Moving too early can cause more sleep problems.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <p class="faq-question">My toddler won't sleep without me. What should I do?</p>
          <p class="faq-answer">This is common and stems from separation anxiety. Try leaving for brief periods and returning, sitting next to the crib instead of holding, or using a lovey (if over 12 months and safe). Consistency is key.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="red-flags">
        <h3>When to Talk to Your Pediatrician</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Snoring, gasping, or breathing difficulties during sleep</li>
          <li>Sleep apnea symptoms (pauses in breathing)</li>
          <li>Persistent difficulty sleeping despite consistent routines</li>
          <li>Excessive daytime sleepiness</li>
          <li>Sleep terrors (screaming, thrashing but not awake)</li>
          <li>Any concerns about breathing during sleep</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
